# Chirp system-ID SITL runner

Automates the Twin Rotor Tailsitter **chirp** actuator system-ID feature in PX4 SITL and
captures **one ulog per chirp**. For each chirp it launches a fresh headless gazebo-classic
SITL, applies that chirp's parameter file over MAVLink, force-arms (the chirp is one-shot on
arm), waits for the sweep, disarms, and saves the ulog.

Related: the feature itself lives in `src/modules/control_allocator` (`ActuatorEffectivenessTwinRotorTailsitter`,
params `CA_CHIRP_*`) and is unit-tested by `functional-ActuatorEffectivenessTwinRotorTailsitter`.

## Requirements

Run **inside the dev container** (`devcon`) â€” the SITL MAVLink ports are container-internal.
Needs `pymavlink` (and `pyulog` for inspection), both present in the container.

## Usage

```bash
# from the repo root, inside the container
python3 Tools/chirp_sysid/run_chirp_sysid.py --chirps cyclic_pitch   # single, smoke test
python3 Tools/chirp_sysid/run_chirp_sysid.py --chirps all            # all 5 chirps
python3 Tools/chirp_sysid/run_chirp_sysid.py --chirps cyclic_pitch,rpm --no-build
```

Results land in `Tools/chirp_sysid/logs/` (gitignored):

```
logs/cyclic_pitch_<UTC>.ulg      # the flight log for that chirp
logs/cyclic_pitch_<UTC>.params   # the exact params used (provenance)
logs/cyclic_pitch.sitl.log       # SITL stdout/stderr for that run (debugging)
```

Useful flags: `--no-build` (skip the up-front `make px4_sitl_default`), `--out DIR`,
`--connect udpin:0.0.0.0:14540`, `--settle`, `--margin`, `--boot-timeout`. See `--help`.

## The chirps / parameter files

One file per chirp under `params/`, in PX4 `param set` syntax (edit freely):

| File | `CA_CHIRP_MODE` | sweeps |
|------|------|------|
| `cyclic_pitch.params`    | 1 | body PITCH â†’ symmetric cyclic |
| `cyclic_yaw.params`      | 2 | body YAW â†’ differential cyclic |
| `collective.params`      | 3 | symmetric collective pitch |
| `collective_roll.params` | 4 | body ROLL â†’ differential collective |
| `rpm.params`             | 5 | rotor motor command (around `CA_CHIRP_RPM`) |

`_common.params` is applied before every chirp (keeps the vehicle armed without RC/GPS).
Default sweep: `0.5 â†’ 15 Hz` over `20 s`, linear (`CA_CHIRP_ORD 1`), rotors held at
`CA_CHIRP_RPM 0.60`.

> **Edit `CA_CHIRP_RPM`** to the normalized motor command that equals ~6000 rpm on your
> hardware/model â€” `0.60` is just a starting point.

## Inspecting a result

```bash
ulog_info Tools/chirp_sysid/logs/cyclic_pitch_*.ulg     # topics + duration (~20 s)
```
Expect (matching the unit tests' routing):
- `actuator_servos` â€” the swashplate/elevon servos oscillate with **rising frequency**.
- `actuator_motors` â€” held ~`CA_CHIRP_RPM` for cyclic/collective chirps; swept for the `rpm` chirp.
- high-rate `vehicle_angular_velocity` / IMU (the `1069` airframe logs `SDLOG_PROFILE 2065`).

## Caveats

- The chirp is **open-loop and bypasses stabilization**, so the vehicle moves/tips on the
  ground during a sweep. That is expected â€” the useful data is the commanded `actuator_*`.
  For clean *response* data you'd run on a constrained test stand or in flight.
- One fresh SITL per chirp â‡’ ~5 gazebo boots for `--all` (a few minutes).
- `CA_CHIRP_*` are live params; logging is configured by the `1069_gazebo-classic_twinrotor_tailsitter`
  airframe (`SDLOG_MODE 0` â‡’ one ulog per armâ†’disarm, `SDLOG_PROFILE 2065`).
- To let the SITL VTOL arm on the bench, `_common.params` disables the airspeed preflight check
  (`CBRK_AIRSPD_CHK`) and auto-disarm (`COM_DISARM_*`); the runner arms in the default mode and
  retries while the EKF converges to a global position.
- `actuator_servos`/`actuator_motors` are logged at ~10 Hz, so content **above ~5 Hz in the logged
  command is aliased**. For analysis, reconstruct the exact command from the chirp equation +
  the `CA_CHIRP_*` values recorded in each ulog (and use the high-rate gyro for the response), or
  lower `CA_CHIRP_F1` to â‰¤5 Hz / raise the actuator-topic log rate.
- The driver sets PX4 INT32 params via the MAVLink bytewise convention (the float field carries the
  integer's bit pattern) â€” see `set_param()` if you add more integer params.
